---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Navbar from "../../components/Navbar.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
import comparisonsData from "../../data/comparisons.json";
import toolsData from "../../data/tools.json";

// SEO Metadata
const seoTitle = "JPEG2000 vs JPEG: Is the Upgrade Worth It? (2026 Guide)";
const seoDescription = "JPEG2000 offers better compression and transparency, but is it actually better than standard JPEG? We compare file sizes, browser support, and image quality side-by-side.";

// Schema for FAQPage and Article
const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": seoTitle,
      "description": seoDescription,
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Image Tool Stack"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between JPEG and JPEG2000?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "JPEG2000 is an updated version of the JPEG format that uses advanced wavelet compression. It offers better image quality at smaller file sizes and supports transparent backgrounds, unlike standard JPEG."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Which format has a smaller file size?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "JPEG2000 files are typically 20-30% smaller than standard JPEG files at the exact same visual quality level."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Should I use JPEG2000 for my website?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "No. While JPEG2000 is technically superior, it has extremely poor browser support. It primarily only works on Apple's Safari browser. For web delivery, stick to standard JPEG or use WebP/AVIF instead."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};

// Get 4 stable related comparisons for the bottom
const relatedComparisons = comparisonsData.comparisons
  .filter(comp => comp.id !== "jpeg2000-vs-jpeg")
  .sort((a, b) => a.title.localeCompare(b.title))
  .slice(0, 4);

const relatedTool = toolsData.tools.find(t => t.slug === "image-compressor");
---

<Layout title={seoTitle} description={seoDescription}>
  <Navbar />
  
  <main class="w-full">
    <!-- Breadcrumbs -->
    <div class="border-b border-hairline bg-canvas">
      <nav class="mx-auto max-w-[1400px] px-6 py-3 lg:px-8 flex items-center gap-2 text-xs font-medium text-mute">
        <a href="/" class="hover:text-ink transition-colors">Home</a>
        <svg class="h-3 w-3" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
        <a href="/compare" class="hover:text-ink transition-colors">Compare</a>
        <svg class="h-3 w-3" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
        <span class="text-ink">JPEG2000 vs JPEG</span>
      </nav>
    </div>

    <div class="mx-auto max-w-[1000px] px-6 py-12 lg:px-8 lg:py-16">
      
      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="text-center mb-16">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-center gap-6 mb-8">
          <span class="flex items-center justify-center h-20 px-6 rounded-2xl bg-canvas-soft font-mono text-2xl font-bold text-ink border border-hairline shadow-sm">JPEG2000</span>
          <span class="text-mute italic text-xl">vs</span>
          <span class="flex items-center justify-center h-20 w-20 rounded-2xl bg-canvas-soft font-mono text-2xl font-bold text-ink border border-hairline shadow-sm">JPEG</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink sm:text-5xl mb-6">JPEG2000 vs JPEG: Is the Upgrade Worth It?</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-body leading-relaxed max-w-3xl mx-auto">
          JPEG2000 was designed over two decades ago to completely replace the standard JPEG format. It promised smaller file sizes, better quality, and transparent backgrounds. So why are we still using standard JPEG today? Let's break down the technical differences.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- Quick Answer -->
      <section class="mb-16 p-8 rounded-2xl bg-canvas-soft border-2 border-link">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-ink mb-6 flex items-center gap-2">
          <svg class="h-6 w-6 text-link" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 10V3L4 14h7v7l9-11h-7z"/></svg>
          Quick Answer
        </h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-body text-lg">
          <p><strong class="text-ink">Use Standard JPEG for:</strong> literally everything on the web. It has 100% universal compatibility across all devices and browsers.</p>
          <p><strong class="text-ink">Use JPEG2000 for:</strong> high-end medical imaging, digital cinema packages, and specialized archival storage where flawless detail is required.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-ink mb-8">The Technical Difference</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-vercel max-w-none text-body">
          <p>
            The original <strong>JPEG</strong> (Joint Photographic Experts Group) was released in 1992. It uses a compression technique called DCT (Discrete Cosine Transform). It works by splitting the image into 8x8 pixel blocks and compressing them individually. This is why highly compressed JPEGs look "blocky."
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>JPEG2000</strong> (.jp2) was released in 2000. Instead of block-based compression, it uses advanced <em>wavelet technology</em>. This allows the format to compress images as a whole rather than in tiny chunks, resulting in much smoother gradients and no blocky artifacts, even at very low file sizes.
          </p>
          
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-ink mt-12 mb-6">If JPEG2000 is Better, Why Did It Fail?</h3>
          <p>
            Despite being technically superior, JPEG2000 never achieved mainstream adoption for three main reasons:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-4">
            <li><strong>Processing Power:</strong> In the year 2000, decoding a JPEG2000 image required significantly more CPU power than a standard JPEG. Most consumer computers and early digital cameras couldn't handle it fast enough.</li>
            <li><strong>Licensing Issues:</strong> Early on, there were fears regarding patent traps and licensing fees associated with the wavelet technology, making hardware manufacturers hesitant to adopt it.</li>
            <li><strong>Lack of Browser Support:</strong> Today, JPEG2000 is still completely unsupported by Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, and Microsoft Edge. It primarily only works on Apple's Safari browser.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Layout>
